<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12117k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12117k">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12117k"> 117(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> black sheep <font face="wake">C</font></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> Un ancien / notaire de Thierry II, Agrestius, qui avait fait profession dans la V&ocirc;ge, donna corps &agrave; toutes ces animosit&eacute;s; il essaya d&apos;attirer les deux successeurs de Colomban dans le schisme des Trois Chapitres; il travailla le m&eacute;contentement de ses fr&egrave;res; il ligua contre Luxeuil les pr&eacute;lats francs; il provoqua la r&eacute;union d&apos;un concile &agrave; M&acirc;con, vers l&apos;an 527, et il s&apos;effor&ccedil;a de jeter le discr&eacute;dit sur la r&egrave;gle que lui m&ecirc;me jadis avait jur&eacute; d&apos;observer. <br><font color="green">[Agrestius, an old notary of Thierry II, who had taken vows in the V&ocirc;ge, embodied all these animosities. He tried to draw Columbanus&apos;s two successors into the schism of the <i>Three Chapters</i>. He applied himself to stirring discontent among his brethren. He united the Frank prelates against Luxeuil. He caused the gathering of a council at M&acirc;con around the year 527 and he strove to discredit the rule that he had once sworn to follow.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 178</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c12121b" href="c12all.htm#c12121b">VI.C.12:121(b)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
